text: ¬†@FILMBRIGHT¬† Whilst the fisheries' scientists, and the Marine Stewardship Council are still in a frenzy to dispute the amazing insight Seaspiracy has given us, I find it stunning that the MSC were given opportunity after opportunity to meet with Ali and Lucy. Time and again they were both turned away. A relative of mine, and a very experienced diver, told me how his diving buddy was almost killed himself when he became entangled in ghost fishing nets in the ocean. He lived because the divers he dived with, risked their own lives to saving him. And yet, this is what the commercial fishing industry is doing every day to our marine wildlife, plants and ocean corals. We really have to do all we can to support Seaspiracy in this mission, the negligence and total lack of regulation for what is happening in our seas is shocking, not to mention the slavery, and starvation of West Africa whose fish are taken illegally while the true inhabitants face poverty and starvation. If you have not seen it, watch the update - fished illegally to be sold back to the true naturals who are now in very dire straits.

text:

We move more sediment than all of the natural forces combined (tidal/wind etc). We can create the conditions of the center of a star. Basically just like North Korea. They launch missiles just to strong arm countries into sending them aide. China would be that x1000. 

Not to say every other country is clean, but China alone makes a MASSIVE impact on the environment and shutting them down would do wonders for healing mother Earth. The bottom line is, pretty or not, China would essentially need to die off for a big move to be made to fix the environment. But no one wants to have that conversation. text:
¬†@Rox¬† Farm pigs, cows, chickens... are artificial bred species. Humans since long time ago bred them from their wild type. The wild species lived and still live in nature providing the habitat in which they live with ecosistemic benefits. For example the wild boar, by eating diferent plants and fruits they contribute to disperse seeds and rhizomes everywhere in the forest; thanks to their digging behaviour soil gets oxygenated helping trees and plants to grow, etc. 
So, answering to your question: farm animals don't provide any benefit to nature because they are artificialy removed from it by humans. If they returned to nature they would eventually play their role in the ecosystem as their wild types do.

text:
Thanks Netflix for covering these very important issues. Also a big thank you to Kip Andersen and all the people that made this documentary possible. This is a great follow up to the other documentaries: "Cowspiracy" and "What the health".
I watched "What the health" about 2,5 years ago. It made me question where my food came from, what it does to my health, the welfare of the planet and the welfare of animals. Sinds then I have done a lot of research and  it send me on a journey to find out what else was hidden out there  that I did not know about. I eventually realized that the way we feed ourselves is correlated with a lot of problems we all collectively face : climate change, animal cruelty, chronic diseases, antibiotic resistance, OVERFISHING, environmental destruction, etc.... 

I have been vegan for about two years now. I don't know anyone personally that is also vegan, except from my little brother who was prepared to listen to me. Going vegan is by far the best choice I have ever made in my life. Thank you very much Kip Andersen and Keegan Kuhn for making this film. It shaped my life in a way I could have never imagined.

text: Great documentary that does a good job covering many of the issues facing the world's oceans and sea life. I've documented nearly all of these issues on my blog in the past, but definitely learned a few things that I didn't know. There is no doubt that the world's oceans are dying and this critical issue is being largely ignored with inadequate excuses and empty promises that we'll stop the devastation in time. That is not likely to happen since the root causes behind ocean pollution and depletion have not been addressed adequately. I do not share the optimism shared at the end for this reason. This is a must sea film [pun intended] for all viewers. The facts presented are shocking, vast and comprehensive - humans have wrecked terrifying damage on a enormous and critical ecosystem that sustains all life on Earth. If you haven't seen this - do so as soon as you can.

text:
¬†@Dariel Rojas¬† I am happy for you.

Here‚Äôs unsolicited advice. Extract what‚Äôs helpful or think of it as a helpful message to others just stating out:

Eat more of the veggies, greens, grains and fruits that you are already accustomed to, and gradually introduce new items to proliferate the new gut microbiomes which help break down the fiber; this is to avoid bloating that many people experience initially upon sudden influx of fiber. For recipe ideas, install the apps such as Fork-over-knives, 21 Day Kickstart from PCRM, Dr Michael Greger‚Äôs DailyDozen recipes, as well as consult pages like this, online and YouTube. The Happy Cow app shows where the nearest vegan restaurant in your area is. Initially, don‚Äôt venture too far on empty stomach whereby you find yourself in weak moments and succumbing to the aromas emanating from the animal products; take some healthy snacks with you. Make sure to supplement with vitamin b12, d3 if you don‚Äôt get enough sunshine every day, a third of a teaspoon of the iodized salt if you don‚Äôt eat seaweeds, as well as flaxseeds, hempseeds, walnuts and chia seeds for your omega 3s. Due to the concept of calorie density, and if you go whole-food plant-based like me, you can have as many servings of soups, salads and curries until you feel full , and will have ingested less calories than an order or two of chicken nuggets. For a healthful education, you can follow the following on the YouTube: Drs Michael Klaper, Milton Mills, Michael Greger, Kim Williams, John McDougal, William Li, Esselstyn, T Colin Campbell, John Furman, Neal Barnard, Will Bulsiewicz as well as the dietitian Lee Crosby and Mic the Vegan, amongst many others.

text:
Powerful and troubling film on so many levels.  The killing of an entire whale pod (babies and all) and comparing it to chickens as justification is ridiculous.  Whales are wild and as such struggle for food/ life daily.  Whales take upwards of 10 years to become mature enough to breed and gestation periods are from 1 year - 18 mons depending on the type (pilot whale).  Mothers only give birth to a few young in her lifetime, 7 years apart.  To compare a life for a life, chicken to whale, a captive farmed species (that multiplies several generations in a year) to a wild species (possibly threatened) is crazy.  Next they'll be comparing whales with flies, a life is a life.

I'm from Canada and we used to have the seal hunt, it was banned for being barbaric and unnecessary and this should be banned too.

I'm sure the fisherman who compared whales to chickens is probably also eating chickens.

text:
¬†@Rich O¬† you need to do your research into the sustainability of egg-laying marine fish. Their sustainability is off the charts. In theory two fish of certain species could repopulate the entire species at its current stock levels in 15 months.  That's how voracious most egg-laying marine fish are. 

So when you talk about what these other scientist and what they have said you're going to have to quote them directly so that I can refute that or agree with it directly.

The sustainability of fish stocks is a very manageable thing but the things that affected are more than just fishing. You have to look at fish like migratory Birds because if you destroy a breeding ground or a feeding ground or a place where they feel safe they will simply go somewhere else or die. Coastal development and factory farming have done more to damage fish stocks than actual fishing

The debris fisherman might leave behind and that's a Mite because that shit cost money is nothing compared to the amount of garbage Americans throw on the ground every day and the amount of plastic pollution put into the ocean by 8 rivers in Asia. The fractional amount of gear left in the ocean is nothing compared to those things which have nothing to do with someone acquiring food or earning a living

text: Whilst the fisheries' scientists, and the Marine Stewardship Council are still in a frenzy to dispute the amazing insight Seaspiracy has given us, I find it stunning that the MSC were given opportunity after opportunity to meet with Ali and Lucy. Time and again they were both turned away. A relative of mine, and a very experienced diver, told me how his diving buddy was almost killed himself when he became entangled in ghost fishing nets in the ocean. He lived because the divers he dived with, risked their own lives to saving him. And yet, this is what the commercial fishing industry is doing every day to our marine wildlife, plants and ocean corals. We really have to do all we can to support Seaspiracy in this mission, the negligence and total lack of regulation for what is happening in our seas is shocking, not to mention the slavery, and starvation of West Africa whose fish are taken illegally while the true inhabitants face poverty and starvation. If you have not seen it, watch the update - fished illegally to be sold back to the true naturals who are now in very dire straits.

¬†@gamwpanagia¬† The main reason have higher rates of cancer now is because we live longer. Just a few generations ago our average lifespan was about 20 years less than it is now. Go back even even longer and our average lifespan decreases even further. Yes, the things we eat and consume can be carcinogenic to some extent (example - red and processed meat is so carcinogenic, there's more cancerous cells in a Big Mac than there are in half a packet of cigarettes), but modern medicine has vastly extended our lifespans making it much more likely to get cancer before we die. 
Also, if everyone became vegan, we'd free up a landmass the size of Africa and stop more greenhouse gases entering our atmosphere than all the world's transportation systems combined. A cow eats 7 times it's own weight before it's slaughtered. Meat is the least sustainable food source we have and if the human population continues to grow at this extent, the price of meat will be so expensive in 100 years the average person won't be able to afford it because demand will outweigh the ability to supply.

author: aureliusVA

text: ¬†@aureliusVA¬† No one lied on the documentary - the statistic of 2048 was created by the fishing industry experts themselves.  Google Jacobin Seaspiracy, watch Sir David Attenborough's 2020 A Life On This Planet.  Sir David Attenborough is a highly respected nature biographer, does that mean he is telling untruths too?  I think not.  Whether you agree with each statistic is your perogative, but the ultimate devastation is all of our concern.  How can we agree to bottom trawling nets that obliterate all fish wildlife and the plants and corals at the bottom of our ocean beds???  A friend of mine was only telling me today how is diving buddy almost died when he too became entangled in ghost fishing nets.  This is what we are doing to our marine life every day.
author: TheFlorence71

text: ¬†@aureliusVA¬† Whilst the fisheries' scientists, and the Marine Stewardship Council are still in a frenzy to dispute the amazing insight Seaspiracy has given us, I find it stunning that the MSC were given opportunity after opportunity to meet with Ali and Lucy. Time and again they were both turned away. A relative of mine, and a very experienced diver, told me how his diving buddy was almost killed himself when he became entangled in ghost fishing nets in the ocean. He lived because the divers he dived with, risked their own lives to saving him. And yet, this is what the commercial fishing industry is doing every day to our marine wildlife, plants and ocean corals. We really have to do all we can to support Seaspiracy in this mission, the negligence and total lack of regulation for what is happening in our seas is shocking, not to mention the slavery, and starvation of West Africa whose fish are taken illegally while the true inhabitants face poverty and starvation. If you have not seen it, watch the update - fished illegally to be sold back to the true naturals who are now in very dire straits.

text: This is a typical Netflix doc in the same style as Tiger King. YES, it touches on a few hugely important issues (human rights, animal welfare, illegal fishing, unsustainable practices, waste) but oversimplifies the overall issue to such an extent it loses it's impact. Simply 'leaving the ocean alone' would condemn millions of the worlds poorest and most vulnerable to starvation (and what about indigenous access and cultural preservation?). This is a massively complicated issue, and the glaring question left is how the doc makers propose to make up the food lost from the sea from production on land with the same or less environmental impact. An interesting doc, but if you're really interested in this, seek out what ocean scientists have to say about it.

text:
If you want to watch a real documentary on the decline of our environment I‚Äôd suggest watching the 2009 documentary ‚ÄúHome‚Äù
This lacks a lot of real journalism. Though I agree the ocean is in need of help the documentary itself just seems like a film maker who googled all of his facts and used facts from the first web page he saw with no real research. 
The sea Shepard ramming multiple shipping vessels and saying that there were no humans harmed? Multi ton vessels ramming each other and nobody gets hurt? I bout it.
Once again I‚Äôm not saying that I disagree with the agenda and thought behind this, I just think that this documentary is doing more harm for the cause by putting out false information. 
Walking into Mitsubishi to ask them about fishing sharks and dolphins? Like did you really think you were going to be able to sit down with someone and actually help the cause or just make yourself seem like a crazy activist to them? If you really wanted answers you could‚Äôve requested for an actual interview then ask them those questions once you get in. Just walking up to one of the most dangerous trades in the world (shark trade) and just walking around with huge video cameras and expecting them not to attack you is just ridiculous. 
There‚Äôs so much more this documentary could‚Äôve been, it had the potential but the facts and emotions got in the way of producing a decent documentary with any credible research.

text:
As a vegetarian going vegan, there are inaccuracies in this documentaries. 

1.) Fish being gone by 2048 was based on a 2006 research paper that has since then have been found not accurate by later studies. The researchers did not intentionally mislead people with their study, they just used the wrong metric. 

2.) MSC is paid off by the fishing industry. This part is a bit fishy. MSC claims that their certifications are carried out by accredited 3rd party bodies. However, you can still get the certification even if you use long line fishing and trawling, which is known to be destructive to sea animals and coral reefs. It seems like MSC's bar is set fairly low that most fisheries can get the certifications. Ineligible fisheries are ones that use poison or explosives to fish, slaves, shark fin violation, etc. 

3.) Some of the people interview have later claimed that their interview was taken out of context. Christina Hicks doesn't give too much information after her initial tweet. 

4.) Seaspiracy highlights Japanese and Chinese fisheries as well as Thai ones too. These are the worst in the industry. USA, Norway, and other European countries are much better regulated in comparison. Their points aren't wrong, but they are taking the worst fisheries to represent a whole. 

After making these points, I'm still not going to eat fish since, by catch of dolphins, over fishing, environmental impact of fish farms, trawling killing environment, etc are all real issues portrayed accurately in this film.

text:
I'm Anti plastic, anti fishing and make sure I do my part. However, I found this documentary extremely superficial. It plays out like a trailer as opposed to an engrossing expos√©. Maybe it's this current generation who can accept such shallow documentary making. Who knows. 

Ali, the documentary maker, is a vegan, as is his entire family. My concern with this current vegan trend is the push for synthetic highly processed genetically engineered "meat" based alternatives, and the increase and acceptance for GM agriculture. If you're not familiar with glyphosphates, then educate yourselves. 

All this documentary did was leave me feeling that there is an undercurrent agenda at play, that perfectly suits the current anti meat pro vegan narrative. 

There is nothing wrong with veganism. There is however, in my opinion, grave concerns about GM agriculture, the long term effects from it on our health, and the effects of it on our ecosystem and ecology. 

Huge geo engineering multinational corporations are behind the majority of the current "plant" based movement and push. 

To any vegans that are reading this message, if you're following veganism, please make sure you're following a healthy vegan diet. Your choices in the products and items that you choose to consume will have an immense impact on health and ecology, therefore choose wisely. Choose natural. Avoid highly processed and synthetic - and opt for organic, if possible.

text:
¬†@Windy Water¬† I am pretty sure most people on this planet care for nature and its animals.

Some industries eager to earn money and power often overrules the effort to do things sustaianble. The doc focuses on these ¬¥bad apples¬¥ but they use the bad apples to mislead the masses into thinking the whole industry, as all global fishing is bad, but that is not true. A big portion of it, especially in Europe, is highly regulated and in many way, not always, big highly at large, is sustaianble.

But since the goal of the vegans behind the doc is not to say people should not eat that kind of fish, but this kind of fish from these areas and countries instead of the bad once, they instead paint a picture as if people should not eat fish at all. And that is wrong, in my eyes

A documentary should be factual and truthfull - through all the documentary, not just parts of it.

Yes, the doc shows areas that are 100% awefull, but they also mislead with wrong facts, exagorated sound and music effects (like when some native islanders have slaughtered some non endangered pilot whales for food) and so on.

Netflix apparently has lower standards than BBC for what documentaries get aired
author: meme me

text: ¬†@meme me¬† Absolutely, definitely agree with the fact that a documentary needs to be based solely on facts. Really shouldn't be called a documentary otherwise.
author: Windy Water

text: ¬†@meme me¬† ¬† agree that it should be factual but on the¬†point on sound effects, the BBC nature documentaries have sound effects all the time to go with the imagery, nothing wrong with that. I don't think all fishing is bad but the bad ones is causing the most harm and the stats in this aspect are mostly correct as I've fact checked some of them. I wish they talk more about the consumer plastic problem as it's really a huge issue.
author: Alice

text: ¬†@Alice¬† All documentaries have some sounds effects, but this is not presented as a nature program, but more as if it was a high standard documentary presenting the world as it is, but in reality it is more edited than a traditional high standard BBC documentary. The doc raised some highly valed points, and I agree with most of them, but I just wish NetFlix had a bit higher standard for what they air, or at least for the future told documentaries to live up to a higher standard if they were to be features on a world stage as Netflix is

¬†@CitizenofGallifrey¬† The rich don't act like that. They follow the money. The fish business will die a lot faster than the fish as the less fish there is it will be harder and harder to get it. Keep in mind the ocean is also producing CO2 and it's quite a producer - the movie also misleads with this!

How much CO2 does the ocean produce?
While previous estimates put the ocean sink at around 2bn tonnes of CO2 per year, we find that it could be 0.8-09bn tonnes larger. Over the whole 27-year study period of 1992-2018, this means the global oceans have taken up 67bn tonnes of CO2 rather than 43bn.
author: Momchil Andonov

text: I witnessed the decimation of an entire population of Tom cod and True cod in the Puget Sound area many years ago when they allowed drag netters in the area for the first time(back in the late 70s or early 80s if I'm not mistaken).  In only a few years they completely raped the area of all cod.  In 1998, I went back to see if the cod had returned, but there was nothing, the entire area that was once abundantly filled with cod is now completely barren!  Before the drag netters came, we'd be able to load the boat up with cod before noontime, and sometimes we'd have a couple salmon as well.  Those days are long gone, a fond memory of something that was but will never be again because as long as greedy men & woman run the system, the "good old days" will never return. üôÑ

text: This documentary is clearly biased and so sensationalised. Aren‚Äôt you supposed to show the truth on both sides of the coin when it comes to documentaries? Also the narrator guy was so annoying to listen to, he doesn‚Äôt back up his facts other than showing his ‚Äúresearch‚Äù and showing a couple of other biased people but never discussing a great alternative like sustainable shellfish/sea veggie practices: farming kelp, oysters, mussels, scallops, and clams, it‚Äôs great for the ocean and for us. He‚Äôs talking to all these random people in the fish industry, clearly trying to get a reaction like he‚Äôs a part of TMZ ‚ÄúWhy do you support overfishing and killing the planet? HUH?‚Äù Like are you interviewing them or protesting? It just seems unnecessary to force the interest on your audience like this on top of the crazy edited and zoomed shots (which by the way is so distracting when you‚Äôre trying to watch anything in general). And don‚Äôt get me wrong, I fully support the message. But sensationalising it only takes away from a documentary like this and even works against the vegan/plant-based movement as a whole. author: CitizenofGallifrey

text:
‚Äã¬†@CitizenofGallifrey¬† YES, we buy all from local fisherman, since processed fish is not economical, you can't find a single processed fish caught by large companies..
And all bycatch is eaten, they sell as "challa"(it's a mix including all bycatch, also I been in this boat, my family friend have one, so I'm pretty confident).
It's the same for our dairy industry. since most the cows are owned by small scale farmers and they sell those milk to govt owned milk society. It, in turn, eliminate large scale cruel factory farm like the USA. Many western companies tried to enter the market(those with factory farm) and they miserably Failed. 
Our system is not perfect but it at least has some decency than other countries.
author: Chetan Krishna

text: ¬†@Chetan Krishna¬† Which country? I'm making a list of interesting countries to perhaps visit if & when travel becomes possible again. Also, within your dairy industry, what happens to the cows when they are no longer able to get pregnant but are still healthy? Are they ‚Äòdisposed of‚Äô as is standard in the dairy industry or are they allowed to live out their natural 20 year lifespan while still being cared for? Because that would be great. Also how much bycatch would you say happens on average? Because as detailed here: greentumble . com / what-are-indicators-of-ocean-health/ the ocean needs a good number of and strong ‚Äòpopulation‚Äô in order to be a healthy eco system & even if bycatch is eaten it‚Äôs still the same amount of dead than if it was dead and then thrown back into the sea.

text:
May be there are not enough statistical data in the documentary, but the fact that so many of the stakeholders refused to be interviewed, cameras being shut down does point to the fact that these people also do not have any data to say that what they're doing is good for the environment. 
And assuming the African population is not at all affected by commercial fishing (as per your logic of having no "data"), the fact that giant companies are allowed to even fish near African coasts is unfair to the native population, they should be the ones fishing there if at all. A man asking for food to these giant ships is not really an indication of their progress.
Moreover, I really don't think that the interview with a slave in Thailand was fake.
The importance of marine biology is already been studied a lot, way before this documentary was made. So the point that most of the carbon is captured in sea is well studied already. 
May be you don't trust the statements given in the documentary about fishing nets being the biggest part of oceanic garbage, you could dig deeper and find sources of this information, if not may be contact the makers. I trust them, but will do it too later. In most of the seal rescue videos, these animals are stuck in fishing nets. This is already enough reason for me to believe that fishing industry is not really a responsible one.

text:
It's obviously a very important issue and we need to reduce fishing by regulation on the UN level. 

But come on, this is a pretty bad documentary. The guy is way too aggressive about his ways, and any time he has an interview he obviously cuts and edits to make it seem like he's getting the responses he wants. 
One interviewee says "My associate can't have said to eliminate fish", the guy says she did, she says "no, there is no way she said to ELIMINATE FISH", then he cuts to her saying to "eliminate or reduce your intake of fish", which is a completely different thing. The documentary then leaves it as that, as if they made a point or something. The interview itself becomes completely irrelevant and any useful information that could have been gotten out of it is lost. 
He "sneaks up" on a fishery and HAPPENS to discover that it's a big tuna fishery. As if that information is not readily available on google. 

The documentary should have focused more on the facts that fishing gear is the greatest part of plastics in the oceans, that dolphins are being killed in attempts to increase the number of fish in the sea, that overfishing is a huge issue.... But instead it's just a cringe worthy attempt at creating "action" out of nothing. 

I hope other higher quality documentaries are made on this issue.

author: mokusinas mokusinas

text: ¬†@mokusinas mokusinas¬† At least 50% of the world's oxygen is produced by phytoplankton, microscopic marine lifeforms. That's what they mean by "water producing oxygen".
author: Andrea LH

text: ¬†@Andrea LH¬† ok,so why do we see all them countries leaders talking about climate change and pollution and never say anything about the waters and plastic garbage in to the oceans...that's a bit strange to me,if we were in trouble with oxygen i suppose some scientists would talk about it and most of the leaders would change the laws of illegal fishing and send them war ships to destroy them pirates...just don't get it why nobody's taking action if it's so dangerous for humans and our future of oxygen...
author: mokusinas mokusinas

text: ¬†@mokusinas mokusinas¬† For many countries, their fishing industry is a huge part of their economy, and we live in a capitalistic world. No country is going to cripple their own economy for the greater good. Also, we're not in trouble with oxygen. There's always gonna be oxygen production. This is not about oxygen, it's about healthy global ecosystems, if the marine ecosystem collapses, it's gonna have massive negative impact on terrestrial ecosystems. We are completely dependent on these ecosystems for food, drinking water, materials, medicine, and other resources. That's what is meant by "mankind can't survive with a dead sea".

text: It‚Äôs propaganda, and not even well-done propaganda. If the filmmakers weren‚Äôt so busy misleading and manipulating their audience, they could‚Äôve actually made good points for a greener and more sustainable future. As it stands though, this trash has zero credibility and belongs in the same  garbage bin as Zeitgeist and Loose Change.
author: Curtis006

text: ¬†@Curtis006¬† What‚Äôs so wrong about it? They‚Äôre pointing out multiple flaws within the industry. Care to elaborate?
author: Link

text: ¬†@Curtis006¬† If it's so flawed then why can't you provide a single point of criticism?
author: Rappa Kalja

text: ¬†@Link¬† where to even begin? The film (I won‚Äôt call it a ‚Äúdocumentary‚Äù) is nothing more than a propaganda piece for veganism, as are the director‚Äôs previous two films I‚Äôve since found out. I haven‚Äôt seen these previous two films, but it seems as though they have the exact same faults, and have been called out as such, from what I‚Äôve read. It blatantly and obviously twists facts and selectively edits its interviews with leading questions to suit the narrative it already pre-determined, and does so shamelessly. It engages constantly in this hackneyed sensationalism and overdramatization. You could almost watch it as a parody. There were moments that were so obviously staged and being sold by the director so poorly that for a moment I questioned whether it was all a Netflix April fool‚Äôs joke. There are, no doubt, a lot of problems in this industry. And I actually agree with the film‚Äôs main concluding thesis: that a social shift towards eating less meat, including fish, collectively, would be of tremendous benefit to the environment and our future. But I fear this film is such an embarrassment that it will hinder that goal rather than help it for years to come. You can‚Äôt get to the world you want by lying and tricking people. Any vegan or environmental activist, if they‚Äôre smart or even just self-aware, should be distancing themselves from this trash as much as possible.
author: Curtis006

text: ¬†@Rappa Kalja¬† I invite you to read my previous post.
author: Curtis006

text: ¬†@Curtis006¬† You said nothing of substance, you just complained that they "dramatized" it. The stats may have been incorrect in some cases, but it is also not possible to know whether stats are truly correct. As a meat and fish eater I fully agree with the message of this documentary and plan on switching to veganism. It is pure hypocrisy to claim to care about the planet and people while arrogantly dismissing this documentary just cause it promotes veganism ?? How ridiculous. Veganism obviously does good for the environment and people. The sole complaint I saw from "experts" is that this documentary tells everyone to stop eating fish and it's not thinking about the poor. This is wrong because it clearly showed how indeginous African populations are struggling to eat and find fish because of commercial and illegal fishing, both markets are heavily unregulated and in fact impossible to regulate as you cannot control what happens at sea. This documentary was directed at an audience that isvprivileged enough to afford a Netflix membership and the devices to watch it, they sure as hell can stop consuming commercial fish.
author: Sarah

text: ¬†@Sarah¬† indigenous African populations struggle to eat and find fish because they themselves use illigal fishing methods and do not adhere to maximum sustainable yield levels set by fishing institutes. In general small-scale fishing is more dangerous to fish than large-scale fishing if you balance out the amount of fish caught
author: Kees Stijne

text: ¬†@Kees Stijne¬† What nonsense you are spewing. Since when catching some fishes to eat is less sustainable than anything else ? You're blaming a few people trying to eat instead of the obvious large numbers of industrial and illegal boats coming there, that you can literally see on footage and images pillaging Africa' vital resources, but whatever fits your narrative
author: Sarah

text: ¬†@Sarah¬† It is by method of how these fish are caught. Large boats can be regulated but individual fishermen going into lakes and using poisons and nets with small mesh sizes cannot.¬†Ofcource 1 fishermen will not do nearly as much damage as a large boat, but if you compare a ton fished through large-scale compared to 1 ton fished through individuals, the small-scale will in general be much more damaging
author: Kees Stijne

text: ¬†@Kees Stijne¬†  Oh my Lord. These industrial boats couldn't be further from regulated and you can literally see on footage these boats catching A LOT of fish and dumping many unwanted dead ones back into the ocean. It's not sustainable at all. It's pure greed for money.
author: Sarah

text: What I'm trying to say is that I agree with Curtis, there are many issues that we need to tackle in the world of seafood production. But a documentary based on people taken out of context and non-truths does more harm than good to the goal of sustainable seafood (which does indeed exist). Many experts on this subject (university professors, certification NGO's, ecologists) have spoken out against this film. And don't claim that large seafood has the whole world bribed, I'm a marine bioloFist and have not seen any money. Maybe it's large vegetable industry that has this producer in their pocket...
author: Kees Stijne

text:
¬†@Sarah¬† and how do you think it happens with individual fishermen? This dumping of bycatch is not allowed in the EU for example. Nobody wants bycatch but there are rules, especially for certification, that try to prevent this from happening. It's a difficult industry, so is all of agriculture, but criticizing NGO'S that try to improve this is not beneficial. I can guarantee you that they ship is not MSC certified. 

Primary production in all sectors is a messy industry, and has a long way to go for sustainability but blanketing an entire industry as "bad" is not a good way to promote a healthy future.
author: Kees Stijne

text: ¬†@Kees Stijne¬† You are literally dismissing so many things with pure dishonesty. With sustainable fishing you are ultimately still killing more, no matter how nice you paint it to be. It is also inherently cruel towards fishes and other sea animals who are proven to feel pain and fear. You might as well call it "sustainable slaughtering", these two words are oxymorons. This documentary takes a standpoint where it takes into account the actual pain and cruelty inflicted on animals, and that's totally valid. You could hear the whales screaming in pain when getting killed. If you don't care, just admit it instead of portraying this documentary as terribly dangerous when it fact veganism is the least harmful thing for the planet and the beings living in it. And please, these EU regulations are meaningless, they cannot and don't control what happens at sea. These labels are all for show and profit, anyone with half a brain knows that.
author: Sarah

text:
¬†@Sarah¬† I care a lot for animals, but the world you paint is black and white. These labels are not for show and profits for the organization that runs them is literally a non-profit organization. You have to start somewhere with sustainability, and veganism is a great place to do so. But veganism is in it self not sustainable, at least not for the vast majority of the world who cannot afford it. But anything taken out of context can be cruel to animals or people alike. Slavery also exists in coffee and chocolate, deforestation for soy and advocado, even the killing of millions of rats and mice to keep grain silos pest free. Does this mean that we should stop eating those products? No, we have to try and find products made in a sustainable fashion. The same is true for seafood and animal production. I am not advocating that there is not a lot wrong in the industry, but punishing those that try to make a difference is counterproductive.

Look at what positives the seafood industry has done, it has transformed one of the poorest states in Vietnam to one of the richest. It has provided micronutrients to the malnourished people of South-Sudan. Lionfish hunting is saving the reefs of Bonaire. When care is taken, the industry can get results for a brighter future, but when left unchecked can do devastating damage. 

Agriculture and fishing is a very difficult industry to understand and regulate. Most people have no idea how it works and thus criticism is easily done, but few offer actual solutions. And those that do should not be burned by a film such as this.
author: Kees Stijne

text: ¬†@Kees Stijne¬† It's so naive of you to think that non-profits are honest, there's so much corruption out there and in case you didn't notice some of these organization  in the documentary have been literally created and funded by corporations running the fishing industry. It's a very common practice in all industries, not just in fishing, to create organizations and bribe audits and certification providers in order to validate their clearly unethical practices. And I don't know about you but I never heard a vegetable scream in pain while being peeled and cut. There's a lot of unfair practices regarding the vegetables and fruits industries but it is not hard to get around that by buying local which is often far cheaper, and growing your own veggies too. However fishing will always remain an obscure and cruel industry no matter how ethical you try to make it,  animals are suffering regardless. Also transparency in terms of the vegan industry is far easier to have, but when it comes to the fishing industry, you simply cannot know what goes on at sea. And after seeing the unnecessary mass slaughter of sea animals, slavery and indigenous populations being deprived of their own resources, I don't think this industry should be supported any longer, that's what this documentary literally advocates for and it is absolutely correct in my view.
author: Sarah

text:
¬†@Sarah¬† so the laws of the government don't work, NGO'S are corrupt and allow for evil cooperations to continue operating under the pretense of sustainability and indigenous people are innocent and know exactly how to manage their own resources? What about the UN's standard development goals? 

You can call me naive all you want but you are starting to sound like a conspiracy theorist... All the experts out there are advocating for change in the seafood industry, me included, but this film does not do the change that has already happened and the people fighting for a better future justice. It is a simple shock factor aimed to get money by getting naive people who have no knowledge of this industry to watch it. And it succeeds at that.
author: Kees Stijne

text: ¬†@Kees Stijne¬† A conspiracy theorist ? It's really not my fault if you don't have awareness of what goes on in the world and what governments, businesses and people in general are capable of doing for money. All these big organizations backed and funded by governments "helping" Africa and poorer countries are completely overlooking the ongoing plundering and theft of Africa's resources, as well as Western countries' complicit implications in these affairs. And they are going to keep overlooking these problems because it is simply in their own interest to do so. You need to think for yourself and use of your own judgement. I'm not saying to deny science and facts, I'm saying be mindful with who communicates the facts, how they do it and what possible biases and interests they may have when doing so. And regardless of how sustainable "sustainable fishing" is, it is still cruel and doesn't take away the pain for animals. It's hypocritical and messed up to claim to care a lot about animals yet be fine with killing them.
author: Sarah

text:
¬†@Sarah¬† ‚ÄúYou need to think for yourself and use your own judgement. I‚Äôm not saying to deny science and facts, I‚Äôm saying be mindful with who communicates the facts, how they do it and what possible biases and interests they may have when doing so‚Äù. 

^ you really need to follow your own advice, Sarah. Seeing the obvious faults in a movie such as ‚ÄúSeaspiracy‚Äù is like a beginner‚Äôs lesson in this regard.
author: Curtis006

text: ¬†@Curtis006¬†  It's shallow and arrogant to dismiss a whole documentary that shows some erroneous stats when the overall message remains just. The damage of fishing is present and visible to anyone who goes near or at the sea.
author: Sarah

text: ¬†@Sarah¬† it‚Äôs just and good to not only dismiss but actively scorn a piece of propaganda that causes more harm than good. Seaspiracy is just that.

author: Sarah

text: ¬†@Sarah¬† Ugh, you‚Äôre brainwashed. I‚Äôve already said several times now that a social shift towards a vegan/vegetarian diet would be enormously beneficial to the globe. That‚Äôs got nothing to do with the movie being harmful trash.
author: Curtis006

text: ¬†@Curtis006¬† You really don't make much sense when your primary complaint is that this documentary is "propaganda for veganisn" & simultaneously admit that it is beneficial üòÇ

author: karen Smith

text:
¬†@Ocean Drop¬† Well that's ridiculous we have sustainable ways in the west. It's the east doing the damage. Especially with whaling and shark fins. 

China has a 10,000 strong fishing fleet that just goes out and destroys everything in it's wake. 
We have fishing bans on some fish for example bass for a few months per year and fishing tuna isn't allowed in some parts. 

We've been fishing our waters for hundreds of years and the stocks are still there because we take care of it. 

Our oysters are also farmed on the coastline which helps clean the water and some even escape and have become wild. 

Films like this make it all seem evil and it's a lie.
author: Paladin Smith

text: ¬†@Ocean Drop¬† We have laws on everything taken from the sea, size limits, female lobsters that have been clipped etc...
author: Paladin Smith

text: ¬†@Paladin Smith¬† the US is hugely involved in the fishing industry, it's not just the east. and not only the US but also other western countries. using the east as a scapegoat won't dismiss the real problem. even if you dont go vegan, there's no denying that reducing our intake of fish is the only way to be environmentally sustainable and to avoid animal cruelty - because there is a difference between catching fish for nutrition on your own versus commercial farmed fishing, that keeps them in confined spaces swimming in their own filth from birth to death.
